Introduction
A facility that uses or stores more than 15,000 lbs. of vinyl acetate is required to submit a Risk Management Program (RMP) to the United States Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA).  An RMP comprises several elements, including an evaluation of potential accident scenarios and a comprehensive program to prevent accidental releases of regulated chemicals. 

The RMP summarizes the management, administrative, procedural, and technological controls that the facility uses in combination to minimize the risk of hazardous chemical releases to the surrounding community.  The RMP includes the following information:

? Introduction;
? Facility identification, regulated substances, and covered processes;
? Policies to protect health, environment, and safety;
? Hazard Assessment;
? Prevention Program;
? Five-Year Accident History;
? Emergency Response Plan; and
? Planned Changes to improve safety

Kinder Morgan Liquids Terminals (KMLT) submitted a 5-year update of the RMP for KMLT?s Argo Illinois Terminal on June 18, 2004.  KMLT has since removed Tank C-11 from cyclohexylamine storage service at the Argo Terminal.  As required by the RMP regulations in 40 CFR 68, Kinder Morgan must update both the RMP and the Accidental Release Prevention Program document to reflect the removal of Tank C-11 from cyclohexylamine service.  Kinder Morgan must also submit an updated RMP to the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA). A copy of the updated RMP is included in Section 8.0 of this document. 

KMLT has updated this RMP for the Argo Terminal by removing all references to the storage of cyclohexylamine in the text, tables, and figures of the RMP and in supporting documentation

